Finding a vaccination appointment analyzing the impfstoffbot account¶

Finding a vaccine in Berlin has been a challenging task. Many different tools to check the availability of appointments in the different vaccination centers area available online. I was frustrated because I couldn't find an appointment for my girlfriend and me on doctolib.com, so I did some analysis on the service by impfstoff.link. Using the twitter API, I downloaded the tweet history of the bot and analyzed the data. I learned what were the times of the day where the service was most updated, how long in the future would the appointment be, and some characteristics of the different vaccination centers. I am proud to say that I got a vaccination appointment for the next weeks using the data I learned.

This notebook analyzes the tweet history of the account @impfstoffbot until 05.06.2021 to try to answer the following questions:

  • Where in Berlin am I most likely to get the vaccine?
  • What time of the day am I most likely to find a vaccination appointment?
  • What is the date where my appointment will happen?

# get locations in tweets

def get_location(text):
    locations = ['Messe Berlin', 
             'Flughafen Tempelhof', 
             'Flughafen Berlin-Tegel',
             'Velodrom Berlin',
             'Erika-He�-Eisstadion',
             'Arena Berlin',
            ]

    for loc in locations:
        if loc in text:
            return loc
    return 'not in list'

In [ ]:
# format time of appintment 

data['time_of_appointment'] = data['Text'].str.extract('(\d+.\d+.\d+)')
data['time_of_appointment'] = pd.to_datetime(data['time_of_appointment'], format='%d.%m.%Y')
data['time_of_appointment'] = data['time_of_appointment'].apply(lambda x : x.tz_localize('Europe/Berlin'))
In [ ]:
# transform UTC in berlin time. This is time tweet was posted

data['Berlin_time'] = data['UTC'].dt.tz_convert('Europe/Berlin')
In [14]:
# extract data from posted tweet time

data['posted_hour'] = data['Berlin_time'].apply(lambda x : x.hour)
data['posted_min'] = data['Berlin_time'].apply(lambda x : x.minute)
data['posted_sec'] = data['Berlin_time'].apply(lambda x : x.second)
In [15]:
# used to analyze month and day sequence

data['posted_month_day'] = data['Berlin_time'].apply(lambda x : pd.to_datetime(str(x.day) + '/' + str(x.month) +'/2021', format='%d/%m/%Y'))
In [16]:
# used to grouop by hour an minute

data['posted_hour_min'] = data.apply(lambda row: row['posted_hour'] + round(row['posted_min']/60,1), axis=1)

Now to the useful part. I don't want to sit on my computer all day refreshing the page aimlessly. So, at what time during the day am I most likely to find an appointment?

If I group by hour of the day, we see some interesting trends. The peak of the available appointments happens at 11am, with an increasing slope starting at around 6am. It is important to note that there have been tweets at every hour in the day, so someone lucky may find something at any point during the day. Still, between midnight and 6am there are the least updates.

Minute analysis¶

The update hours don't seem to follow any specific pattern. A person may be responsible to update the times whenever more vaccines are available, or there may be a complex scheduling scheme to make appointment booking truly random. But I'm guessing if there is a trend in the minutes (7:35, 8:35, 9:35, etc.) in case there is a scheduling system:

When will my appointment occur¶

The tweets contain the information of when will the available appoitnments happen. Getting some statistics of the time difference between the tweeted time of appointment and the actual time where the tweet was posted, we can gather some information:

In [19]:
data['time_diff'] = data['time_of_appointment'] - data['Berlin_time']
In [20]:
data['time_diff_days'] = data['time_diff'].apply(lambda x: x.days)

In general, it seems that the average waiting time between the tweet and the appointment is 31 days, but having a standart deviation of 24 means that the data varies a lot. This is confirmed by havig a maximum waiting time of 80 day, and minimum of 1, where you would get an appointment for the next day.

In [24]:
print('mean:', data['time_diff_days'].mean())
print('std: ', data['time_diff_days'].std())
print('max: ', data['time_diff_days'].max())
print('min: ', data['time_diff_days'].min())

mean: 31.906315058986813

In Messe Berlin, the mean and std waiting time are lower. This seems a good location to get vaccinated.
